article.description: P.J. Dozier scored all six of his points in overtime, including a 10-foot, baseline jumper at the buzzer to give South Carolina a 70-69 win against Monmouth on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Dozier's jumper lifts South Carolina over Monmouth in OT
article.linkText: Dozier's jumper lifts South Carolina over Monmouth in OT
article.story: COLUMBIA, S.C. -- P.J. Dozier scored all six of his points in overtime, including a 10-foot, baseline jumper at the buzzer to give South Carolina a 70-69 win against Monmouth on Tuesday night. Sindarius Thornwell had 23 points, nine rebounds and six assists, Duane Notice scored 15 points and Chris Silva added 10 with 10 rebounds for South Carolina (3-0). Dozier's game winner came after Monmouth's Je'lon Hornbeak converted a 3-point play to give the Hawks a one-point lead with 1:02 remaining. "P.J. was not where he was supposed to be," said USC coach Frank Martin. "He was kind of in no man's land. I think maybe he was trying to get in position for a rebound." As it turned out Dozier was ready to receive a pass from guard Notice that set up the final shot. Chris Brady led Monmouth (1-1) with 17 points. The Gamecocks opened the game with a 13-0 run and a layup by Thornwell gave them their biggest lead, 40-22, with 15:23 left in regulation but Collin Stewart answered with a 3-pointer, sparking a 16-3 run that pulled the Hawks within four fewer than five minutes later. Diago Quinn's putback with 6:52 left gave Monmouth its first lead, 52-50. Thornwell answered with a 3-pointer and, after an offensive foul called on the Hawks' Austin Tilghman, a put-back layup and the Gamecocks didn't trail in regulation again. "At the end of the season they don't ask how you won, just how many you win," said USC coach Frank Martin. "I told our team I don't want to be the Grinch that stole Christmas, but we played offense like a bunch of nine-year olds tonight." Monmouth's Micah Seaborn hit two free throws with 19 seconds remaining to send it to overtime. "We're physical, but they guarded us across the whole court," said Monmouth coach King Rice. "Those guys tonight were hard to deal with, so all credit to them. They made one more shot than we did." Two free throws by Hawks guard Justin Robinson tied the game at 50 with 7:48 remaining. BIG PICTURE South Carolina: After missing the NCAA Tournament despite winning 24 games last season, the Gamecocks claimed their second straight victory over a team that participated in the postseason following the 2015-16 campaign. South Carolina topped Holy Cross, a NCAA tourney participant, while Monmouth was a No 1 seed in the NIT. UP NEXT USC returns to action Friday when it hosts South Carolina State. The team then goes on a five-day break before hosting Michigan on Dec. 23. Monmouth (1-1) will play its third game of the season Friday when remains on the road against Syracuse. The Hawks return home to host Cornell on December 22 before going back on the road. Five of Monmouth's first seven games are on the road. TURNING POINT After stretching a seven-point lead to 18 with 15:23 remaining, South Carolina appeared headed to an easy victory but Monmouth used 26-8 run to tie the game at 50 with 7:46 left in regulation. BULLET POINTS South Carolina continues to be a guard-dominated offense early in the season. Sindarius Thornwell, Duane Notice and P.J. Dozier entered averaging 46.5 of the team's 83-point average. The trio scored 44 of the Gamecocks 70 points Tuesday. Monmouth center Chris Brady, who entered the game averaging 13 points and six rebounds, kept the Hawks in contention with several key rebounds and big baskets in the second half. He finished with 17 and 10 rebounds to lead four Hawks players in double figures. Hornbeak scored 14, Micah Seaborn 11 and Justin Robinson had 11 points. Monmouth coach King Rice a former assistant coach at Vanderbilt and player at North Carolina entered with a great knowledge of the South Carolina program. "I feel connected to this program because of (Monmouth assistant coach and former Gamecocks' assistant) Rick Callahan and (former South Carolina coach) Eddie Fogler," said Rice. "I think they have good kids."
